The paper deals with the Local Computation Algorithms (LCA) model, which is a computational model for solving problems with huge inputs and outputs. The focus is on graph problems and the probe complexity of LCAs that work on graphs with arbitrarily large degrees. This suggests that the paper could belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with randomized and deterministic LCAs, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category. The paper also deals with graph theory and combinatorics, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) sub-categories. Finally, the paper deals with information theory in the context of randomized LCAs for finding a maximum matching, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category.
